          "page_0": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "It was a hot September afternoon in 1961. Somewhere in Lakeside, Connecticut, Tom Vasell, CC ’62—one of the Ivy League’s most prolific passers—had just gone through a grueling football practice. After his eighth practice in four days, Vasell’s entire body was aching. It was a feeling the New Jersey native knew well."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Camp Columbia, the football team’s annual preseason training camp, was in full swing. Entering his third and final season on the varsity squad, Vasell was used to both the pain of two-a-days and the pain of losing seasons."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“We had all done this before,” he said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "After practice, Vasell and his teammates would drink a concoction made by assistant coach John Toner to recharge. It was made of cider, water, vinegar, and honey—“bug juice,” they called it. It was not glorious, but it did the job for Vasell. However, he thirsted for something even sweeter—his first taste of victory."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Columbia had been one of the least successful teams in the Ivy League since the conference’s formalization in 1954. The Lions had not finished in the top half of the Ancient Eight in five years; they had earned only four conference wins in the last two seasons combined. Still, led by a talented group of seniors—including Vasell; halfback Russ Warren, CC ’62; captain and left guard Bill Campbell, CC ’62; and all-Ivy tackle Bob Asack, CC ’62—Columbia possessed a sense of optimism which seemed out of place for a team that had finished dead last in the Ivy League only two years prior."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“We’re victory-hungry,” Vasell said in a 1961 preseason interview with Spectator. “The fellows realize that this is our last chance to win a whole lot of football games.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Three years earlier, these seniors were first-years competing for Columbia’s “Cub team.” At the time, first-years were not eligible to play varsity football. Instead, they played a five-game season against other first-year teams from across the conference. The uncharacteristically large 1958 Cub squad, specially brought in by head coach Aldo “Buff” Donelli to eventually build the varsity squad into a winning program, had high expectations entering the season. Vasell remembers his coaches riled the team up in preseason workouts with the slogan, “Let’s go, five and oh!”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The young Cubs had good reason for their confidence. Donelli recruited a talented group, which according to Vasell, had three quarterbacks jostling for the starting job and “big, stout linemen who were bigger than most varsity players.” Warren even recalls embarrassing the varsity team in a scrimmage."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I think it was the last time they scrimmaged us because we actually dominated the game,” he said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The team did not deliver on its coaches’ hopes of going undefeated, but it still turned in a winning 3-2 record—“unheard of” for Columbia football, according to Vasell."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[As first-years], we knew that Columbia had not done well, and we thought that we should try to establish ourselves as being potentially a good team in the future,” Warren said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "While the first-years were turning heads with their impressive play, the varsity squad was solidifying itself as one of the Ivy League’s bottomfeeders. In 1958, the Lions went 1-6 in Ivy play, better only than a winless Yale team. The following year, many members of the ’58 Cub team, now sophomores, moved up to the varsity squad. Yet success on the field was still hard to come by. In 1959, the Lions again won a lone Ivy League game, and in 1960, they won only three."
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "width": "auto",
                "asset": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/WZHBY65AFZELLLAHT3EQINXSZ4.jpg",
                "caption": "",
                "credit": "Image courtesy of Columbia Athletics"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“We were young guys bucking against some very good competition, and it was tough,” Vasell said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Given Columbia’s historic woes, those outside the team expected nothing better from the Lions ahead of the 1961 season. Outsiders anticipated that Donelli’s squad would have yet another subpar showing, with preseason polls projecting a sixth-place conference finish for the Light Blue."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Stanley Waldbaum, CC ’62, the then-sports editor of Spectator, wrote before the season, “If practically no one gets hurt, if a few key sophomores come through, and most important of all, if Buff Donelli’s nineteen experienced seniors get fighting mad, then no Ivy League squad will have a chance against the Lions. But if not, then once again, Columbia will be doomed to the dreary depths of the second division.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In a league where senior experience reigned supreme, the class of ’62 hoped that their time to run the show was coming that year. But before the Lions could take such a big leap, something else would need to happen. Namely, they would need to create an environment where the team’s success came before individual fun. At the time, “the concept that a bunch of players or starters would go out and have 20 beers on a Saturday night was not a weird concept,” Joe O’Donnell, CC ’64, said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“During several past seasons morale on the Columbia squad was not very high,” Waldbaum wrote that season. “Often its leaders were unable to stem the rash of curfew-breakings and half-hearted practice performances of the third and fourth stringers and this would soon affect the whole team.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In essence, the team needed to surmount “an old culture of accepting losing,” as Vasell put it."
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "width": "auto",
                "asset": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/BSGSL3PFUNFUTMVEASAFK6Z3FA.jpg",
                "caption": "",
                "credit": "Image courtesy of Columbia Athletics"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Their plan to overcome such a deep tradition?"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“A combination of a lot of senior leadership and then a terrific captain in the form of <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/sports/2019/11/21/bill-campbell-gave-columbia-his-time-and-money-but-his-biggest-gift-was-generations-of-mentorship/\">Bill Campbell</a>.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Campbell—who earned the nickname “Ballsie Campbell” in his Cub days—and the other seniors took on what seemed to be an impossible task: setting a standard of discipline and accountability, which shaped everything from practice intensity to nightlife."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Campbell, Donelli, and assistant coach Don Savini, were key figures in enforcing the team’s 10:30 p.m. curfew, which had not been adhered to in the past. Not only that, he and the other seniors decided to create a no-partying policy during the season."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“We just all took the game seriously,” O’Donnell said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "This level of intensity translated to the practice field, too. The team came out of Camp Columbia “in terrific condition”—especially crucial in an era when players played on both offense and defense and the number of game substitutions was limited. Despite the Lions’ struggles over the previous years, “We all felt we could win,” Warren said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The players’ confidence was only reinforced when they went back home to Morningside Heights after Camp Columbia and handled Bucknell University 18-8 in a preseason scrimmage. Still, the Lions were not satisfied. In a break from tradition, Campbell convinced his teammates to return to Camp Columbia for extra training ahead of their Ivy opener."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“We’re ready,” Campbell told Spectator in 1961."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "It seemed like the perfect storm. Columbia had one of the Ivy League’s best quarterbacks in Vasell; an explosive backfield consisting of Warren, junior Tom O’Connor, CC ’63, and senior Tom Haggerty, CC ’62; and all-Ivy linemen in Campbell, Asack, and senior Tony Day, CC ’62."
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "width": "auto",
                "asset": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/4O6ON6SCTJGTLCOMSYC2JJOIKU.jpg",
                "caption": "",
                "credit": "Image courtesy of Columbia Athletics"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "To put the cherry on top, Donelli was a legendary coach with even more legendary life experiences. He had coached in the National Football League, played soccer for the U.S. men’s national team, and served in the U.S. Navy during World War II. With these myriad experiences to draw from, Donelli was a fitting leader for a group that hungered to experience success for the first time."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Buff was extremely smart, maybe one of the smartest people I have ever met,” O’Donnell said. “He had a great perspective on human nature.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Vasell echoed this sentiment: “He knew how to handle men.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "With a strong nucleus of seniors, an unwavering belief in their abilities, and a hunger to achieve what they never had, the Lions were ready to take on the Ivy League."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "First up: Brown."
            }
          ],
          "page_1": [
            {
              "type": "subhed",
              "value": "Week 1: Brown vs. Columbia—Saturday, Sept. 30, 1961"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week1score.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "With their preseason victory over Bucknell under their belts, the Lions traveled to Providence, Rhode Island, to take on the Brown Bruins in their Ivy League opener on Sept. 30. Brown had a young, inexperienced squad, with only five seniors on its 53-man roster. Columbia, meanwhile, had 17 returning lettermen, the most in the Ivy League."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Lions had dominated the Bruins 37-0 the year prior. This time, they one-upped that performance, putting on an offensive clinic in Providence. It only took Columbia’s second touchdown, a 56-yard connection between Vasell and Warren, to “[break] the spirit of the Providence team,” according to Spectator writer Conrad Sherman."
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "width": "auto",
                "asset": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/KSFOPCDTV5B55HVM3YZGSOFVG4.jpg",
                "caption": "",
                "credit": "Image courtesy of Columbia Athletics"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Lions proceeded to score on each of their next two possessions and play all 43 of their healthy players. Columbia rushed for 295 yards, led by the three-headed monster of Haggerty, O’Connor, and Warren, who scored three touchdowns. By the time all was said and done, the scoreboard read “Columbia 50 Brown 0”—the Light Blue’s largest victory, ever."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It appeared to all the New Englanders that Buff Donelli, like the Norse God Thor, had hurled a lightning [sic] bolt at their fair city,” Waldbaum wrote after the game."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Winning in such dominant fashion against Brown was certainly a confidence boost for the Lions, but they knew that they had bigger fish to fry—or rather, tigers to cook."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Sure we were looking forward to next week’s game against Princeton,” Warren said. “We want to win that game more than anything else in the world. But the coaches reminded us that we had a job to do here today, and do it we did. Actually, we all figured that Brown would be a lot tougher than it was.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Donelli just had one thing to say to his team: “Stay healthy. There is a long season ahead.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "With that, the Light Blue returned home and set its eyes on its next challenger, the Princeton Tigers."
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week1standing.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "subhed",
              "value": "Week 2: Princeton vs. Columbia—Saturday, Oct. 7, 1961"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week2score.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Columbia victories against Princeton were rare—the last time the Lions beat the Tigers had been in 1945, when first-years Gene Rossides and Lou Kusserow led the Light Blue past the Tigers 32-7. Columbia victories against Princeton at home were even rarer: The last time Princeton lost at Baker Field was in 1932."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "To make matters worse, the Lions had not been able to muster a single point against Princeton in three years. However, hopes were high this year: Columbia went into the game as the favorite, according to the New York Times. Princeton head coach Dick Colman even praised the offensive “quickness” and “tremendous” defense of the Light Blue ahead of their week two matchup."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "This was a big game for the Lions. Not only would a victory break the Lions’ losing streak, it would also crown their Homecoming game. A pep rally was held to stir up school spirit that week. “We will try to acquire some of the pride in athletics which exists at Princeton,” an announcement read. “The Columbia varsity football team needs your support Friday night.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Over 23,000 gathered at Baker Field on a game day marked by boiling heat. Despite the Lions’ historic woes against the Tigers, Columbia was confident it could vanquish its “perennial tormenters,” as Spectator writer Alan Willen dubbed Princeton."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "With alumni and students alike cheering them on, the Lions struck first. On Columbia’s opening drive, O’Connor broke out for a 46-yard touchdown run, putting the Lions on the scoreboard."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Lions did not relent as O’Connor punched in another score to put the Lions up 14-0. At this point, Donelli put the backups in. The crowd buzzed with excitement at the thought of Columbia finally breaking the curse."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "But unlike the previous week’s opponents, the Tigers were not done fighting just yet. On the last play of the first quarter, Princeton’s Hugh Macmillan connected with Jim Rockenbach at their own 35. Rockenbach took it the remaining 65 yards, making it a one-possession game."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The momentum shifted. The Princetonians in the crowd were now the primary noise-makers."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The second unit did not get another chance to play after this defensive lapse. In the second period, Rockenbach took the ball 28 yards for his second score. Princeton converted on the ensuing two-point attempt to take the lead 15-14."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In the second half, Warren, who ended the day with 102 yards on the ground, punched in a touchdown to regain the lead 20-15. The Tigers responded with a 12-play, 75-yard drive that ended with a score for Princeton. Then Princeton’s Greg Riley put the icing on the cake in the fourth quarter with an 87-yard touchdown run."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "It was a physically grueling game—due to the heat, Warren lost 16 pounds, and Black lost 20—and a devastating loss for the Lions, who had hoped they could finally take Princeton down. Warren, who played through a nose injury, called it “probably the most disappointing game I ever played in.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Still, there were many positive takeaways. “I feel better about this team’s ability than I did after the Brown game,” Donelli said following the loss. “They showed that they could run, that they could pass, and that they could defend against a real good football team.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Lions would have to forget their disappointment and put their sights on their next challenger—Yale, the reigning Ivy League champion."
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week2standing.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "subhed",
              "value": "Week 3: Yale vs. Columbia—Saturday, Oct. 14, 1961"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week3score.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Bulldogs, fresh off an 18-0 win over Connecticut, were riding an 11-game winning streak, the longest in the nation. Nevertheless, Yale head coach Jordan Olivar was rather pessimistic for a man whose team had not lost a game in nearly two years."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“There’s no doubt that the ‘experts’ were wrong about our team. There is no comparison between this squad and last year’s,” Olivar said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Though Yale’s 1960 team went undefeated and ended the season as the No. 14 team in the nation according to The Associated Press, after losing 10 starters, the new Yale team bore little resemblance to the previous year’s. As Olivar put it: “We have no depth.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "However, Yale had a talented quarterback in Bill Leckonby and a powerful running game built around fullback Ted Hard. In addition, Columbia would be without Haggerty, who suffered a charley horse against Princeton. While the Bulldogs may not have been as strong as they were the previous year, no one expected them to be a walk in the park."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Much like a middle-aged banker, Yale is solid, formidable, and conservative,” Spectator writer Reed Strauss wrote."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Joining another crowd of over 23,000, the Light Blue traveled to the Yale Bowl in hopes of ending the Bulldogs’ streak. However, the Bulldogs started strong, as Hard and fellow fullback Dick Niglio came out of the gates with a fast attack. The duo combined for 26 yards on four consecutive plays before a penalty stifled the Yale offense. At the 7:30 mark of the first quarter, Al Butts, CC ’64, picked off Leckonby’s pass, but the Lions could not convert on the interception."
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "width": "auto",
                "asset": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/TPHPRMAUEFGIRH7V6QO23CWGEY.jpeg",
                "caption": "",
                "credit": "Image courtesy of Columbia Athletics"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Butts, a sophomore thrust into the starting lineup in the wake of Haggerty’s injury, would become the game’s unexpected hero. In the second quarter, Butts ran to the end zone for the game’s first and only touchdown. He then scored himself on the ensuing two-point conversion."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Neither offense was able to gain an edge from that point on. Vasell threw two interceptions, but Yale could not capitalize. Midway through the fourth quarter, Butts intercepted another Yale pass to ice the game. O’Connor later kicked a field goal to end the scoring at 11-0."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Butts had been a reliable defensive player in the past, but even Donelli did not expect his heroics: He ended the game with 66 yards, two key interceptions, and the game’s only touchdown. His performance earned him Ivy League Back of the Week honors."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "After the previous week’s gut-punching loss to Princeton, snapping the Bulldogs’ winning streak was rejuvenating for the Light Blue—and other Columbians."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "After the victory, the Columbia University Marching Band marched to “Roar, Lion, Roar” on Yale’s campus. In retaliation, a group of Yale supporters attacked the band and stole its glockenspiel. X-rays later revealed that one Columbia tuba player left the scene with a bruised bone and torn leg muscles. Regardless of the damage, “the Blue never broke formation, and left the Eli campus proudly playing ‘Who Owns New York?’” Spectator writer Peter Trooboff, CC ’64, reported. Columbia did what would have been unthinkable only months before."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“If we beat Yale we have a good chance to beat anyone in the league,” Donelli said prior to the game. Next, Columbia would test its luck against Harvard."
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week3standing.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "subhed",
              "value": "Week 4: Harvard vs. Columbia—Saturday, Oct. 21, 1961"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week4score.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Lions traveled to Cambridge to avenge an injustice: a year-old Homecoming robbery. One year earlier, Harvard, down 7-6 at Columbia’s Homecoming, went for a go-ahead two-point conversion, which was deemed successful by the umpire, giving the Crimson an 8-7 victory. An NBC film later revealed that Harvard had not actually converted and that the Crimson ballcarrier was actually stopped before crossing the plane."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Lions were looking to right last year’s wrong in what turned out to be a pivotal Ivy League game. Harvard was without seven players, including starting quarterback Ted Halaby. The Lions, meanwhile, would be welcoming back Haggerty after he sat out against Princeton."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Much like Olivar the week before, Harvard head coach John Yovicsin was not particularly confident in his team: “I don’t know if the boys will be up for the game. I wish I could read their minds.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The first quarter saw little action, with neither team scoring, but that did not last long. In the second quarter, O’Connor broke through the Harvard line from six yards out to open up the scoring. Shortly after, Haggerty punched one in of his own from the Harvard nine after the Crimson had turned it over off of a high snap on a fourth down punt attempt."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Harvard quickly responded by scoring on a fourth down passing play after junior Hank Hatch returned Warren’s kick-off 66 yards and put the Crimson in great field position. Harvard fans roared in approval."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Columbia quickly silenced the Cambridge crowd. This time, it was Warren’s turn—before the end of the half, he ran it in for six more points."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Crimson controlled the third quarter, scoring again to narrow the Columbia lead down to 20-14. However, Harvard would make another fatal error. In the fourth, Harvard quarterback Mike Bassett threw a lateral pass, only for it to be intercepted by the Light Blue. Haggerty proceeded to score his second touchdown of the day on a one-yard drive, sealing the deal 26-14."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Lions’ three-headed running back crew stuffed the stat sheet. On 60 carries, Warren, Haggerty, and O’Connor combined for 244 yards and scored all four of Columbia’s touchdowns."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Once again, Columbia won handily, and once again, the CUMB made its presence felt. The Blue Band entered Cambridge with an 8-foot-4-inch drum made of paper and wood, mocking Harvard’s famous 6-foot-6-inch drum. Five of Harvard’s drummers tore apart the imitation drum, and 50 Columbia fans rushed the Harvard band and the giant drum in response but failed to do any damage."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The win marked the Lions’ third in Ivy League play and the first time the team had won consecutive Ivy League games in a decade. A conference title was well within reach, but Donelli kept a level head. “Let’s not look ahead too far,” he said. “But we’re still in the ball game, I guess.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week4standing.html"
              }
            }
          ],
          "page_2": [
            {
              "type": "subhed",
              "value": "Week 5: Columbia vs. Lehigh—Saturday, Oct. 28, 1961"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week5score.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Following its conquering of Harvard, the Lions’ second win in a row, Columbia was riding high. Its next game represented a break from Ivy play; the Lions would instead take on Lehigh University."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Lehigh was a considerable opponent on a winning streak of its own. Against Columbia, that streak would continue. The Engineers dominated on the ground, beating Columbia at its own game to take home a 14-7 win."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The ironically perverse lady who controls the fortunes of football gave the Columbia Lion a cruel slap in the face in the second half of Saturday’s contest against Lehigh after caressing him and leading him on during the first,” Spectator writer Barry Landau wrote."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Columbia deserved to lose,” Waldbaum wrote. “Its line was outplayed and the entire team was outhustled by a fired-up band of Pennsylvanians determined to show up the New Yorkers.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Had the Lions already peaked? Was the Lehigh game a sign of things to come?"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I just think we played a bad game,” Toner said. “No one can be singled out for under-par play. The whole team was under-par.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Lions would have a week to feel “ashamed,” as Strauss thought they should, before they got another chance to take on the Ivy League."
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week5standing.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "subhed",
              "value": "Week 6: Cornell vs. Columbia—Saturday, Nov. 4, 1961"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week6score.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "At this point in the season, the race for the Ivy title was tightly contested. Princeton, sitting at the top of the table with a 3-0 record, was rolling. Columbia, at 3-1, trailed closely behind the Tigers, with Yale, Dartmouth, and Harvard hot on the Lions’ tails."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Cornell appeared to be an easy opponent on paper. Plagued by injuries, the Big Red was winless in the Ancient Eight. However, the previous week, Cornell put up a strong fight against Princeton, while Columbia played one of its worst games of the year against Lehigh. Moreover, Warren’s status was still in question after he suffered a bruised left knee in the game against Harvard."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Columbia was still a heavy favorite, and Cornell head coach Tom Harp knew that: “It’s been a nightmare of a season,” he said bluntly. “We’ll be outmanned by Columbia on Saturday.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Lions seemed to have taken the Lehigh loss to heart and dominated most of the game. Less than three minutes in, O’Connor ran 33 yards to the end zone to cap off a 74-yard drive. However, Cornell responded later in the quarter, taking the lead 7-6 on a 35-yard touchdown pass. Later in the half, Cornell punter Dave McKelvey booted it deep into Columbia territory, and Haggerty stunned the Ithaca crowd by returning the punt 84 yards—the longest return in Columbia history—to regain the lead for the Lions."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The run did more than set a record; it turned the tide against a scrappy Cornell squad that had overcome an early Columbia touchdown to take a 7-6 lead,” Spectator writer Ira Youdovin wrote. “No psychiatrist was necessary to diagnose the demoralizing effect Haggerty’s stunner had on the home side.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "After the floodgates opened, Columbia could not be stopped. The Lions marched to a 35-7 victory as Haggerty completed two marvelous touchdown runs from 47 and 64 yards out."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Haggerty’s record-breaking performance was one for the ages. In addition to his 85-yard return record, Haggerty set Columbia records for yards from scrimmage with 148, and points against an Ivy opponent with 18. Despite the heavy workload they had been taking on, Haggerty and his fellow running backs showed no signs of slowing down."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Cornell’s injury-ridden 11 had not tested the Lions, but the Light Blue still trailed Princeton in the standings. What’s more, Columbia would face down a formidable opponent the next week: Dartmouth."
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week6standing.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "subhed",
              "value": "Week 7: Columbia vs. Dartmouth—Saturday, Nov. 11, 1961"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week7score.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Columbia, Dartmouth, and Harvard had all lost only one Ivy game, behind only undefeated Princeton. For this reason, beating Dartmouth was of paramount importance for the Lions."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Columbia would be playing an Ivy opponent in front of its home crowd for the first time in over a month, drawing over 25,000 spectators in its largest crowd yet that season. The Lions were out for blood, and they did not fail, securing a dominant 35-14 victory."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The defense shined in this one. Day, continuing his marvelous season on both sides of the ball, swatted Dartmouth’s Tom Spangenberg’s pass on the Dartmouth 10, which wide receiver Dick Hassan, CC ’62, fell on in the end zone to give Columbia the first points of the game. Then, on the very first play after the ensuing kickoff, Columbia forced a fumble, recovered the ball, and eventually took it to the end zone yet again as Vasell found Hassan for six."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Columbia shored up its lead in the third quarter, when Haggerty ran the show. On the Lions’ opening drive of the second half, Haggerty carried the ball 13 times for 46 yards, capping the drive off with a two-yard touchdown run. To close out the third, he did nearly the exact same thing, carrying the ball 10 more times for 45 yards and a touchdown to give Columbia a 20-point lead."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Warren put the icing on the cake by breaking away for a 43-yard score with under 2 minutes left in regulation. It was Columbia’s fifth touchdown of the game, but something bigger had happened. Just moments before, Harvard had beaten Princeton 9-7, meaning that Harvard, Columbia, and Princeton would hold a three-way tie for first place in the Ivy League as soon as the clock read zero."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "As Columbia only had one Ivy game remaining, a win the following week against Penn would guarantee co-champion status at the minimum. Princeton had two games remaining, one against Yale and the other against Dartmouth, and Harvard still had to play Brown and Yale. So in order to become the sole possessors of the Ivy League trophy, the Lions would need some help. “I’d like to see you beat Princeton,” Donelli told Dartmouth coach Bob Black after the game."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Something had changed. An excitement now surrounded Columbia football. Donelli began to receive telegrams from Columbia alumni who now “feel that it’s all possible. This was an attitude that was previously absent at Columbia,” Donelli said. After five straight losing seasons, Buff Donelli was a winner again."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "On campus, there was a new sense of school spirit shared among students, which student board chairman Dave Tucker, CC ’62, described as “tremendous.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“The interest on campus grew from week to week,” Waldbaum said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The buzz was not only important for the football team, though. “This means a great deal to me,” said Dave Tomkins, CC ’62, the chief drum beater at pep rallies. “I’ve taken a lot of ribbing from my friends at other Ivy League schools in the past. I’m proud as the devil.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Ancient Eight crown was right there for the Lions. One more win was all it would take."
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week7standing.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "subhed",
              "value": "Week 8: Columbia vs. Penn—Saturday, Nov. 18, 1961"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week8score.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "At 5-1, the ball was in the Lions’ court. If they beat Penn, they were guaranteed a tie for first place at the very least; a loss would make their position precarious at best."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Penn, Ivy League champions only two years earlier, had a significant edge in the all-time matchup. Columbia had not beaten Penn at home since 1934. The Quakers had beaten Columbia by a combined score of 66-6 in 1958 and 1959, and no Penn team had ever lost to Columbia in consecutive years."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "However, “the pendulum [had] swung” in Columbia’s favor, Sherman observed. In 1960, Columbia took down Penn for the first time in 23 years. Now, the Lions sat at the top of the Ancient Eight, while the Quakers found themselves in sixth place, a region of the standings Columbia was used to inhabiting."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Despite the changing of the guard, Penn head coach John Stiegman’s confidence did not falter. “Sure, we’ll be up for Columbia,” he said. In preparation, Stiegman planned to move five reserves into the starting lineup to rejuvenate his squad, a decision that puzzled Donelli."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Who are they?” he asked."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "While beating Penn was their main goal, the Lions were also looking for some help from Yale, which was set to play Princeton that week. “I guess that everyone at Columbia must be wearing both light and dark blue clothes this week,” Olivar joked."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Yale did not mind helping the Lions out. “If we don’t win it will be nice if one of the strangers to the Ivy title does,” Olivar added. “Princeton has won before.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The stage was set. As long as the Lions handled their business in front of their home crowd, history would be made. If they failed, then it would be up to the football gods to decide their fate."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "With their squad nearly at full strength, Columbia left nothing up to chance, blowing Penn out of the water 37-6."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "With Columbia up 3-0, thanks to a field goal from O’Connor early in the first quarter, the Quakers were forced to punt from their own end zone as a Warren punt cornered them in their own territory. The Penn punt would not go far. Hassan broke through a line of Quakers and smothered the punt, which Black caught in the end zone to give the Lions’ their first touchdown."
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "width": "auto",
                "asset": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/FUHLUSTXSRCQTJQ64M3JCEZMGI.jpg",
                "caption": "",
                "credit": "Image courtesy of Columbia Athletics"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In the second quarter, Columbia went back to its bread and butter. The Lions’ three primary backs rushed 10 times in a drive as Warren scored to increase the lead to 17. Before the close of the half, Dick Sakala, CC ’64, would run it in from 40 yards on a quarterback draw, making the score 23-0. The dominance continued in the second half: Haggerty, who had a dazzling 68-yard run in the third quarter, scored his 10th touchdown of the year, before Vasell converted on a quarterback sneak to conclude the scoring for the Lions."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Time expired. It was over; the job was finally finished. The Lions did the unthinkable. They were champions."
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "width": "auto",
                "asset": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/IZJHGOKJIJCDJGOGCPHZ44ZLVM.jpg",
                "caption": "",
                "credit": "Image courtesy of Columbia Athletics"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“We didn’t think at the beginning that we could win the championship,” Donelli said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“This is very much a team.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Lions—athletes, coaches, students, and administrators—were filled with jubilation. When asked how he felt, athletic director Ralph Furey responded, “Pretty good. Yes, wonderful; I think that you can see from the people around here that this has been a shot in the arm for the entire Columbia family, and it will spur our other teams on.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Now, all the Lions had to do was wait."
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week8standing.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "subhed",
              "value": "Week 9: Harvard wins both, Princeton falls to Dartmouth after beating Yale"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week9score.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In week eight, Harvard beat a winless Brown team, boosting its record to 5-1. The Crimson’s final matchup was against Yale, which had failed to beat Princeton in week eight. Ahead of the game, Vasell, Campbell, and Warren sent the Bulldogs a telegram wishing them luck against Harvard. However, the Lions’ efforts to boost their temporary allies did not bear fruit as Harvard shut Yale out 27-0. Yale came up short for the Lions once again."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Columbia lost to Rutgers 32-19 that week, but the game did not count toward the Ivy League standings."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "After beating Yale, Princeton lost to Dartmouth in its season finale 24-6. That meant that Columbia and Harvard would share the title as each held a 6-1 record. Meanwhile, the Tigers’ loss bumped them to 5-2, putting them out of title qualification."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Vasell, Donelli argued to the coaches committee that the Lions should be the sole owners of the title since they had beaten Harvard earlier in the year. However, it was not to be—Columbia and Harvard were co-champions. Despite the potential for ill will because of the decision, the team was not bitter, according to Vasell."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“We were happy to be champions.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "week9standing.html"
              }
            }
          ],
          "page_3": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The legacy of the 1961 team"
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "width": "auto",
                "asset": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/ERF4MJSK2ZD4JOKJTPU24J3CGQ.jpg",
                "caption": "",
                "credit": "Image courtesy of Columbia Athletics"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The 1961 football team went down as Columbia’s most iconic."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Aside from a week two loss to Princeton, the Lions steamrolled through the Ivy League. In their seven Ivy games, they outscored opponents by 143 points, an average margin of victory of over 20 points. Meanwhile, Harvard—Columbia’s co-champion—only outscored opponents by 83 points."
            },
            {
              "type": "graphic",
              "value": {
                "asset": "pointdiff.html"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The team featured a relentless running attack led by three elite backs—O’Connor, Haggerty, and Warren—who never failed to deliver. The trio combined for over 172 rushing yards per game and accounted for over 20 touchdowns that season. Their effectiveness was reinforced by the strength of the offensive line, which featured three all-Ivy Leaguers."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "While Columbia’s offense got most of the attention, its defense was outstanding as well. The Lions held opponents to only 13 points per game on 212.7 yards per game, indicating a rock-solid defense."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The 1961 team still dominates Columbia’s record books. Seven of its seniors were named to Columbia’s All-150 team. Additionally, the Lions’ 50 points in their 50-0 thrashing of Brown still holds the record for the most points scored against an Ivy opponent in Columbia history, and their 6-1 Ivy League record remains the winningest Ivy season Columbia has ever had. The team was inducted into the Columbia Athletics Hall of Fame in 2010."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Yet none of the Lions’ successes would have happened without their veteran leaders, namely Campbell. Campbell spearheaded a movement that made winning a priority in the football program, enforcing the team’s 10:30 p.m. curfew and bringing a new level of intensity to practices."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Even after graduation, Campbell was the glue that kept the team together. According to O’Donnell, the late Campbell would organize get-togethers with his former teammates, covering the airfare and other costs for those who did not have the financial means to attend."
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "width": "auto",
                "asset": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/AG2XENKVMNG2NJ6LLODDZPUAUY.jpg",
                "caption": "",
                "credit": "Image courtesy of Columbia Athletics"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Campbell and Waldbaum developed a close relationship at Columbia that continued through their adult lives, with Campbell never failing to thank Waldbaum for his support of the team."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“[Campbell] was an extraordinary human being,” Waldbaum said. “He had this ability to make everybody around him feel that they were part of the team. It transcended the mere playing of football for him.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "For many of the 1961 Lions, the relationships they formed are what they cherish the most about that season. O’Donnell recalls Donelli telling him many years after 1961, “You know, one thing about your whole group is that you always supported one another.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "width": "auto",
                "asset": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/VN2WMKQGFBAGHFBYKCP7QBH744.jpeg",
                "caption": "",
                "credit": "Image courtesy of Columbia Athletics"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“What has stuck with me the most over the past 60 years has been the friendships and camaraderie over six decades,” Vasell said. “We first met each other as freshmen in 1958. We rode the bus to Baker Field every day to and from practice, and we forged a bond over a common love of football.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Playing on the 1961 team meant more than just winning Columbia’s first Ivy League football championship; it was a transformative experience that helped the players transition to life after Columbia."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Being a part of something, having to work physically very hard to do it, and to put up a disappointment but still have a successful outcome ... teaches you a lot about things in general, in terms of saying, ‘OK, things didn’t work, but you overcome it. You make success the next week.’ That’s a lesson that’s good in any part of life,” Warren said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Many of the players from the 1961 team still follow Columbia football closely. Warren, who has been a team doctor for the New York Giants for the past 35 years, said he goes to games each season. Sometimes, he also recommends players on whom he operates to look into Columbia."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Columbia still looking for second title"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Sixty years later, the Lions are still on the hunt for that elusive second title."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“At this juncture, I am a little surprised that Columbia has not won another Ivy League football championship,” Vasell said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Lions got close in 2017. Their 5-2 Ivy League record was the best in recent memory, but it was not enough to win the conference. It is difficult to pinpoint an exact reason for such a long drought, but Warren has some hypotheses."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Columbia’s never been known as a real football school in general, so those kinds of records are sort of self-perpetuating just from a recruiting point of view,” Warren said. “It’s very easy for other schools to tell recruits, ‘Well, why do you really want to go there if you’re not gonna win a lot of games?’”"
            },
            {
              "type": "image",
              "value": {
                "width": "auto",
                "asset": "https://cloudfront-us-east-1.images.arcpublishing.com/spectator/3NDQMLYLERG27FY4JLNHVUIZGU.jpg",
                "caption": "",
                "credit": "Image courtesy of Columbia Athletics"
              }
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "While the 1961 Lions belong to an exclusive club that consists of only them, many long for the day when their alma mater will be able to repeat their success."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Quite frankly, I’m tired of hearing about the ’61 team or the last three winning seasons and stuff like that,” O’Donnell said. “That’s not something that should be saluted. That’s something that should be considered an embarrassment.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It’s time we started talking about the class of 2022 winning the title,” he added."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Yet there is reason for optimism. Warren, O’Donnell, and Waldbaum are all strong believers in head coach Al Bagnoli, who won nine Ivy League titles at the helm of Penn’s program."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I think [Bagnoli], who in my view is the smartest coach there since Buff, [has] a shot,” O’Donnell said. “I don’t think anybody wants him to succeed more than the group that was there when I was there.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Lions have started the year 3-1, their only loss coming in their <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/sports/2021/10/02/princeton-pulls-away-in-fourth-quarter-to-give-lions-first-loss-of-season/\">Ivy opener</a> against Princeton. With a full slate of Ivy League games ahead of them, their potential to win the title will soon be put to the test."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "This year’s squad also shares several similarities with the 1961 team. Led by seniors Dante Miller and Ryan Young, the Lions possess a fierce rushing attack with multiple options, much like the running core of O’Connor, Haggerty, and Warren."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Light Blue’s 10 fifth-year “super seniors” have provided veteran leadership, paralleling the 1961 team’s nucleus of senior leaders, and just like the 1961 team, this year’s Lions were tested by a strong Princeton squad early in the season."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“If you look at the schedule, you could have a similar thing from 1961,” Waldbaum said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "With a plethora of young talent on the roster—including sophomore quarterback <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/sports/2021/09/28/he-didnt-want-to-be-promised-anything-joe-greens-path-to-columbias-starting-quarterback-role/\">Joe Green</a> and a junior varsity squad that is tearing through opponents—the Lions may not be far from their second title. But until then, the 1961 team will remain Columbia’s one and only champion."
            },
            {
